This is a '''list of presidents of the [[History of Medicine Society]]''' of the [[Royal Society of Medicine]].
Numerous distinguished authors and historians became presidents and many more were invited to speak.<ref name=":Hunting"/>
==1912-1931== {| class="wikitable" |- ! Years !! Name !! Comments !! Image |- | 1912–1913 || [[William Osler|Sir William Osler]]<ref name=":Hunting">{{Cite book|title=The History of The Royal Society of Medicine|last=Hunting|first=Penelope|url=https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=hFNrAAAAMAAJ&q=penelope+hunting+royal+society+of+medicine+osler+330&dq=penelope+hunting+royal+society+of+medicine+osler+330&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwikkt7qgN3bAhUBMqwKHabuAOEQ6AEIJzAA|publisher=Royal Society of Medicine Press|year=2002|isbn=1853154970|location=|pages=330–333}}</ref> ||British Canadian, known as "king of pranks", Osler was one of the "big four" founding members of the [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]] where he had arrived in 1888 as physician in chief. He is best remembered for establishing the medical residency programme, taking medical students to the bedside, writing major textbooks<ref name = "Big Four">[http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/about/history/history5.html Johns Hopkins Medicine: The Four Founding Professors]. Hopkinsmedicine.org. Retrieved on 18 June 2018.</ref> and whilst in England as Regius Professor of Medicine at Oxford, founding the history of medicine section at the RSM in 1912. [[Raymond Crawfurd]] described him as a “magnet” in attracting members. Undeterred by opposing Sir Richard Douglas Powell who felt the Society had too many sections already, Osler meticulously planned the establishment of the History section, individually writing to more than 160 potential members. He considered the section one of his better achievements in his later years and his wish was for it to be a common meeting place for “scholars, students and all those who feel that the study of the history of medicine has a value in education”.<ref name=":Hunting"/>|| [[File:William Osler c1912.jpg|thumb|100px|William Osler]] |- | 1913–1916 || [[Sir Norman Moore, 1st Baronet]]<ref name=":Hunting"/> ||British physician, lecturer in [[anatomy]] and [[pathology]] and historian, Moore is best known for his connection with the [[Royal College of Physicians]], [[General Medical Council|GMC]] and his writings on [[history of medicine]].<ref name="MunksMoore">{{Cite web|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/6749|title=Munks Roll Details for Norman (Sir) Moore|last=|first=|date=|website=munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref> To his disappointment he did not make the first president as Osler had recommended.<ref name=":Hunting"/> || [[File:Sir Norman Moore.jpg|100px|thumb|Sir Norman Moore]] |- | 1916–1918 || [[Sir Raymond Henry Payne Crawfurd]]<ref name="Dodds">{{Cite journal|last=Dodds|first=Charles|last2=Payne|first2=L.M.|date=1963|title=Sir Raymond Crawfurd|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of Medicine|volume=56|issue=Suppl 1|pages=19–24|issn=0035-9157|pmc=1896754|pmid=14044492}}</ref>||Crawfurd graduated in classics from [[New College, Oxford]] in 1888, before studying medicine. Primarily physician and lecturer at King’s College, he became its medical Dean and major player in moving the hospital to Denmark Hill, for which he was knighted in 1933. Due to chronic illness, he left active medicine and wrote on history of medicine, publications including, ''The Last Days of Charles II'' (1909), ''The King's Evil'' (1911) and ''Plague and Pestilence in Literature and Art'' (1914).<ref name="Munksroll">{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=G.H.|title=Raymond Henry Payne (Sir) Crawfurd|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/1063|website=munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk|publisher=Royal College of Physicians|accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref> || |- | 1918–1919 || [[D'Arcy Power|Sir D'Arcy Power]]<ref name=":Thomas1996">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/36506805|title=Presidents of the Royal Society of Medicine : illustrated profiles, 1805–1996 : Dr. William Saunders to Sir Donald Harrison|last=Henderson |first=Moll, J. M. H. (John) Michael|date=1996|publisher=Royal Society of Medicine Press|isbn=1853152641|location=London|pages=265–266|oclc=36506805}}</ref> || Physician at St Bartholemew’s, Power was a prolific writer of medical history.<ref name="RSoc">{{cite journal|journal=Proceedings of the [[Royal Society of Medicine]]|year=1963|volume=56|pages=24–25|title=Sir D'Arcy Power| first=W. R.|last=LeFanu|pmc=1896749|pmid=14044493}}</ref> He later recalled how the section was “more like a family than an integral part of a great scientific society”.<ref name=":Hunting"/>|| [[File:D'Arcy Power Sydenham Medical Club portrait. Wellcome L0028823.jpg|thumb|100px|D'Arcy Power]] |- | 1920–1922 || [[Charles Singer|Professor Charles Singer]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.ox.ac.uk/wellcome-unit-history-medicine|title=Wellcome Unit for the History of Medicine {{!}} Faculty of History|website=www.history.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-07-25}}</ref> || Physician, pathologist and historian, he was invited to Oxford by William Osler in 1914, later becoming professor in history of medicine at University of London in 1930. One of the original history section members, Singer retained his position as editorial representative for twenty three years and maintained a high quality of the section’s publications. He supported refugee scholars fleeing Nazi Europe and is known for his many publications of short histories. He kept a miniature set of traffic lights to control lengths of speakers, switching to red when they became dull or prolonged.<ref name=":Hunting"/><ref>https://europepmc.org/backend/ptpmcrender.fcgi?accid=PMC1896860&blobtype=pdf</ref> || [[File:Charles Singer, working at his desk. Wellcome L0012188.jpg|thumb|100px|Charles Singer]] |- | 1922–1924 || [[Sir Arnold Chaplin]]<ref name=":ObituaryCharles Singer"/>|| After studying at St. Bartholomew’s Hospital Singer's primary appointment was at the City of London Hospital for Diseases of the Chest, where he remained for the next twenty-nine years. He co-authored the textbook on ''Fibroid Diseases of the Lung'', and ''The Science and Art of Prescribing'' and wrote ''The Illness and Death of Napoleon Bonaparte'' (1913). He loved old books and prints, and became Harveian Librarian at the Royal College of Physicians.<ref name=":ObituaryCharles Singer">{{Cite web|url=http://ghgraham.org/text/tharnold1864_obit.html|title=Obituary of Dr. Thomas Hancock Arnold Chaplin|last=Graham|first=George H.|date=|website=ghgraham.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref><ref name="Brown">{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=G.H.|title=Thomas Hancock Arnold Chaplin|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/815|website=munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> || |- | 1924–1926 ||[[John Davy Rolleston]]<ref name=":Proceedings1962">{{Cite book|title=Proceedings of the royal society of medicine – 56 – 1963 – supplement|last=|first=|publisher=H K Lewis & Co. Ltd.|year=1962|isbn=|location=Royal Society of Medicine Library|pages=1–9}}</ref>||An original member of the Section, he was a member of the council, secretary and president.<ref name="MunksRollJohnDRolleston">{{Cite web|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/3844|title=Munks Roll Details for John Davy Rolleston|last=|first=|date=|website=munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=3 July 2018}}</ref>|| |- | 1926–1928||[[Walter G. Spencer]]<ref name="ObituarySpencer">{{cite journal|title=OBITUARY|journal=BMJ|date=9 November 1940|volume=2|issue=4166|pages=649–652|doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4166.649}}</ref> || Known as "The Historian of Westminster" by fellow medics || |- | 1928–1930 ||[[Herbert R. Spencer]]<ref name=ObitSpencer>{{cite journal|title=OBITUARY|journal=BMJ|date=13 September 1941|volume=2|issue=4210|pages=389–390|doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4210.389-a}}</ref> ||Obstetrician who wrote about [[William Harvey]], midwifery and [[external cephalic version]].<ref name=ObitSpencer/> || |- | 1930–1931 || [[Humphry Rolleston|Sir]] [[Humphry Rolleston]]<ref name=":masthead">{{cite journal | url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1896746/pdf/procrsmed00213-0002.pdf | journal = Proc R Soc Med|volume= 56|issue=Suppl 1|year= 1963| title = masthead| pmc=1896746}}</ref> || 57th president of RSM.<ref name=":masthead"/> || [[File:Sir Humphry Davy Rolleston. Photograph by A.C. Cooper after Wellcome V0028779.jpg|thumb|100px|Humphry Rolleston]] |-
