==1931-1960== {| class="wikitable" |- ! Years !! Name !! Comments !! Image |- | 1931–1933 || [[Robert Oswald Moon]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=G H|title=Robert Oswald Moon|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/3171|website=munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk|publisher=Royal College of Physicians|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> ||Consulting physician to the National Hospital for Diseases of the Heart and the [[Royal Waterloo Hospital]] and a staunch [[Liberal Party|Liberal]], and a member of the [[Reform Club]]. His main interest was in the [[classics]] and was demonstrated in his book on ''The Relation of Medicine to Philosophy'', his [[Fitzpatrick Lecture]] before the [[Royal College of Physicians]] in 1921 on [[Hippocrates]] and his successors. He witnessed "three wars and contested five general elections".<ref name="LancetMon1953">{{cite journal |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0140673653911532 |title=Robert Oswald Moon, D.M. Oxfd, F.R.C.P., J.P. |journal=[[The Lancet]] |volume=262 |issue=6780 |date=8 August 1953 |page=303 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(53)91153-2}}</ref> || |- | 1933–1935 || Sir [[St Clair Thomson]]<ref name=ClairLives>{{cite web|url=http://livesonline.rcseng.ac.uk/biogs/E004711b.htm |title=Thomson, Sir St Clair - Biographical entry - Plarr's Lives of the Fellows Online |publisher=Livesonline.rcseng.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-08-27}}</ref> ||Wrote book ''Diseases of the Nose and Throat'' and was president of the Royal Society of Medicine between 1925 to 1927.<ref name=ClairLives/> ||[[File:St Clair Thomson1.jpg|thumb|100px|St Clair Thomson]] |- | 1935–1937 ||[[Edwin Goodall]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=G H|title=Edwin Goodall|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/1807|website=munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk|publisher=Royal College of Physicians|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> || || |- | 1937–1939 || [[Alexander Polycleitos Cawadias]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Franklin|first1=A W|title=Alexander Poly